The chunk is situated within the **Hiding and Showing** section of the document, which details methods to temporarily prevent objects from rendering on all or specific cameras. It includes code examples for both Python and C++, demonstrating how to hide/show objects and use camera masks for per-camera visibility control.

Context: This section explains techniques for controlling object visibility in the scene graph using NodePath methods like hide(), show(), and camera masks, providing practical code examples.

cpp

myNodePath.set_alpha_scale(SA);

Hiding and Showing

To temporarily prevent an object from being drawn on all cameras, use ~.NodePath.hide() and ~.NodePath.show():

python

myNodePath.hide()
myNodePath.show()

cpp

myNodePath.hide();
myNodePath.show();

If you want to hide an object for one camera but not another, you can use the ~.NodePath.hide() and ~.NodePath.show() commands in conjunction with the .Camera.set_camera_mask() function:

python

camera1.node().setCameraMask(BitMask32.bit(0))
camera2.node().setCameraMask(BitMask32.bit(1))
myNodePath.hide(BitMask32.bit(0))
myNodePath.show(BitMask32.bit(1))
# Now myNodePath will only be shown on camera2...

cpp

camera1.node()->set_camera_mask(BitMask32::bit(0));
camera2.node()->set_camera_mask(BitMask32::bit(1));
myNodePath.hide(BitMask32::bit(0));
myNodePath.show(BitMask32::bit(1));
// Now myNodePath will only be shown on camera2...
